body:
I haven't found a more official source directly addressing this point, but [this blog post](https://kendaleiv.com/setting-regex-timeout-globally-using-dotnet-6_0-with-csharp/) seems to explain it:
>[setting the global default timeout] needs to happen as early as possible (first statement in Main would work), prior to any usage of `Regex` that causes this value to be read and cached. Once itâ€™s cached it cannot be changed without restarting the application.

More specifically, it looks like once the default timeout value is set, you can still set new values via `domain.SetData` and read those values with `domain.GetData` without throwing errors, but new `Regex` objects won't actually use the new values.  Here's a console app I tested with:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Text.RegularExpressions;

public class Example
{
    public static void Main()
    {
        AppDomain domain = AppDomain.CurrentDomain;

        Console.WriteLine("Creating object regexBefore");
        Regex regexBefore = new Regex("foo");
        Console.WriteLine($"regexBefore timeout: {regexBefore.MatchTimeout}\n");

        Console.WriteLine("Setting to 1 seconds.");
        domain.SetData("REGEX_DEFAULT_MATCH_TIMEOUT", TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1));
        Console.WriteLine($"GetData Result: {domain.GetData("REGEX_DEFAULT_MATCH_TIMEOUT")}\n");

        Console.WriteLine("Creating object regexAfter");
        Regex regexAfter = new Regex("foo");
        Console.WriteLine($"regexAfter timeout: {regexAfter.MatchTimeout}\n");

        Console.WriteLine("Setting to 2 seconds.");
        domain.SetData("REGEX_DEFAULT_MATCH_TIMEOUT", TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        Console.WriteLine($"GetData Result: {domain.GetData("REGEX_DEFAULT_MATCH_TIMEOUT")}\n");
    }
}

// Output:
// Creating object regexBefore.
// regexBefore timeout: -00:00:00.0010000
// 
// Setting to 1 seconds.
// GetData Result: 00:00:01
// 
// Creating object regexAfter
// regexAfter timeout: -00:00:00.0010000
// 
// Setting to 2 seconds.
// GetData Result: 00:00:02
```

So I think what's probably happening is that some private/internal usage of `Regex` causes `REGEX_DEFAULT_MATCH_TIMEOUT` to be cached before your class library has a chance to set it to something else.
